<br>
It is difficult to do, especially when he taunts and invades your real life, but what he really wants is attention, probably attention he isn't getting/hasn't gotten from his parents. Ignore him. If he posts, don't respond, don't even read it if you know it is him. As soon as he comes back under a new guise, ignore that one, too. If he finds he no longer causes a stir, he will probably go away. He is enjoying this attention. Children are like that, even negative attention is preferable to no attention.<br>
<br>
And under no circumstances should anyone do anything to him in real life. Even encouraging it could wind you up in the lawsuit. If some wack-job who thinks they are defending the Honor of FV, or some other lunacy that wack-jobs think up, does do some harm to this kid, everyone who encouraged it could end up in civil court. Criminal court, probably not, but civil court is far more lenient about who can be involved (witness the OJ Criminal v. Civil trials). I worked as an insurance investigator for several years, the type of lawyers who handle these cases name anyone and everyone they think they can get a penny out of in their suits. <br>
<br>
Worse still, what if something happened and the kid took his story to one of the newsmagazines, a 20/20 or Dateline or something? And they decided it was about time to make gamers look like idiots again, and decided to do a story? There he sits, an innocent child, distraught parents saying how horrible it is, he was a kid playing games and those evil, evil adult gamers ganged up on him... I can hear the byline now... &quot;Next on Dateline... What happens when on-line gaming goes off-line...&quot;  (accompanied by appropriate creepy-weirdo music and a flickering computer screen image in a dark room). <br>
Next thing you know, all the non-gamers out there think we are freaks again.<br>
<br>
Ignore him.<br>
<br>
